# TeaQL Tool Architecture Design

## Motivation

As TeaQL evolves from a query framework into a business programming platform, we need a unified and constrained tool surface for both developers and AI coding agents.

Instead of allowing arbitrary access to thousands of Rust crates, TeaQL introduces a stateless tool registry:

```rust
T::time().now()
T::json().parse("{}")
T::text().trim(" hello ")
T::id().uuid()
```

The goal is not to replace Rust's ecosystem.

The goal is to provide a stable, readable, AI-friendly, and implementation-independent API surface.

---

# Design Principles

## 1. Stateless

Tools should not depend on business state.

Good:

```rust
T::time().now()
T::text().trim(s)
T::json().parse(s)
```

Bad:

```rust
T::auth().current_user()
T::tenant().current()
T::workflow().move_to(...)
```

Business state belongs to:

```rust
Q:: Query
E:: Entity
A:: Action
L:: Lifecycle / Logic
```

not Tool.

---

## 2. Domain Neutral

Tools represent common knowledge.

Examples:

```rust
T::time()
T::json()
T::text()
T::decimal()
T::regex()
```

Tools should not contain industry-specific knowledge:

```rust
T::gas()
T::erp()
T::invoice()
```

Those belong to domain modules.

---

## 3. AI Friendly

A coding agent should only need to understand a small set of namespaces:

```rust
Q::
E::
A::
L::
T::
```

instead of thousands of third-party APIs.

This dramatically reduces API entropy.

---

## 4. Stable API Surface

Business code depends on TeaQL APIs.

TeaQL internally chooses implementations.

```rust
T::json().parse(...)
```

may use:

```rust
serde_json
simd-json
other implementation
```

without affecting business code.

---

# Core Tool Categories

## Minimal Profile

Available by default.

```rust
T::time()
T::id()
T::decimal()
T::text()
T::json()
T::regex()
T::code()
T::hash()
```

These cover the majority of business applications.

---

## Extended Profile

Optional features.

```rust
T::money()
T::validate()
T::list()
T::map()
T::csv()
T::excel()
T::image()
T::unit()
T::geo()
T::crypto()
T::template()
T::random()
T::diff()
```

---

# Crate Architecture

## teaql-tool-core

Contains only:

```text
Traits
Interfaces
Errors
Common Value Types
Feature Registration
```

No heavy dependencies.

---

## teaql-tool-std

Contains commonly used tools:

```text
text
json
time
id
decimal
regex
code
hash
```

Expected to be the default package.

---

## teaql-tool-extra

Contains optional heavy features:

```text
csv
excel
image
geo
unit
template
crypto
random
diff
```

Only loaded when required.

---

## teaql-tool

Facade crate.

Provides:

```rust
T::time()
T::json()
T::text()
```

and re-exports enabled implementations.

---

# Feature Gates

Example:

```toml
[features]

default = ["minimal"]

minimal = [
    "text",
    "json",
    "time",
    "id",
    "decimal",
    "regex",
    "code",
    "hash"
]

business = [
    "minimal",
    "money",
    "validate",
    "list",
    "map"
]

data = [
    "minimal",
    "csv",
    "excel",
    "diff"
]

full = [
    "business",
    "data",
    "image",
    "geo",
    "unit",
    "crypto",
    "template",
    "random"
]
```

