# Example Mapping

## Time

```rust
T::time().now()
T::time().today()
T::time().parse_date(...)
```

Possible implementation:

```text
chrono
time
```

---

## JSON

```rust
T::json().parse(...)
T::json().stringify(...)
T::json().diff(...)
```

Possible implementation:

```text
serde_json
json_patch
```

---

## ID

```rust
T::id().uuid()
T::id().ulid()
T::id().snowflake()
```

Possible implementation:

```text
uuid
ulid
nanoid
```

---

## Excel

```rust
T::excel().read(...)
T::excel().write(...)
```

Possible implementation:

```text
calamine
rust_xlsxwriter
```

---

## Image

```rust
T::image().resize(...)
T::image().thumbnail(...)
```

Possible implementation:

```text
image
fast_image_resize
```

---

# Long-Term Vision

TeaQL Tool is not a utility library.

It is a constrained programming surface.

Developers and AI agents interact with:

```rust
Q::
E::
A::
L::
T::
```

instead of directly depending on thousands of third-party APIs.

This provides:

* Better readability
* Better portability
* Better AI coding experience
* Easier dependency management
* Stable long-term architecture

Ultimately, TeaQL Tool becomes the trusted common toolbox for business programming.

